        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7588.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to R. H. Blair, [before 16 March 1871]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7590.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. H. Blair, 16 March 1871</ref>. CD had asked Blair, who was the principal of the Worcester College for the Blind Sons of Gentlemen, about expression of emotions by the blind.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, p. 352, CD cited Blair for the information that those born blind displayed most expressive actions as well as the sighted, and suggested that this was explained by the fact that these expressions were inherited.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, pp. 311–12, CD cited Blair for the information that children born blind blushed.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3782.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henry Philpott</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD did not visit Worcester in 1871. No further correspondence between Blair and CD before the publication of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref> in 1872 has been found, but the details that appear in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, pp. 312 and 352, and not in this letter, suggest that they did correspond further.</note>
        </div>        
            
